'''''SummerSlam 2007''''' was the twentieth annual [[SummerSlam]] [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] event produced by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE).<ref name="Sellout"> {{cite web|title=SummerSlam sellout|url= http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/archive/summerslam07soldout|publisher=WWE|date=[[2006-12-30]]| accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> It took place on [[August 26]] [[2007]] at the [[Continental Airlines Arena]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]].<ref name="SLAM! Review">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2007/08/27/4450221.html|first=Nick|last=Plummer, Dale and Tylwalk|title=Returns highlight SummerSlam|publisher=SLAM! Sports|date=[[2007-08-27]]|accessdate=2007-10-24}}</ref> Tickets for SummerSlam 2007 went on sale on [[December 30]], and sold out in 40 minutes.<ref name="Sellout"/> The official theme song was "''[[Whine Up]]''" by [[Kat DeLuna]] w/[[Elephant Man (musician)|Elephant Man]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/inside/overtheropes/news/katdeluna|title="Whine up" to SummerSlam |publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-09-03|last=Medalis|first=Kara A.|date=[[2007-07-26]]}}</ref> The tagline for the event was "''The Biggest Party of the Summer''".<ref>{{cite web|first=Greg|last=Adkins|date=[[2007-08-27]]|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/exclusives/summerslam20|title=SummerSlam Review|accessdate=2007-10-25|publisher=WWE}}</ref> The secondary tagline was "''The Party is Over''".

The main event was for the [[WWE Championship]] between [[Randy Orton]] and [[John Cena]], which Cena won after an [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]].<ref name="SummerSlam - Orton vs Cena">{{cite web|first=Bryan| last=Robinson|date=[[2007-08-26]]|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/3900088/results/|title=Champ's legend lives on|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref> The main matches on the [[undercard]] were [[The Great Khali]] versus [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] and [[John Hennigan|John Morrison]] versus [[CM Punk]] for the [[ECW Championship]].<ref name="SummerSlam - Khali vs Batista">{{cite web| first=Louie|last=Dee|date=[[2007-08-26]]|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/39000883/results/|title=Punjabi robbery|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SummerSlam - Morrison vs Punk">{{cite web|first=Lennie|last= DiFino|date=[[2007-08-26]]|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/3900088311/results/|title=Enlightened robbery| publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref>

==Report==
===Background===
[[Image:Cena With Spinner Belt.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[John Cena]] as [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]].]]
The main [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] heading into SummerSlam on the ''[[WWE Raw|RAW]]'' [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]] was between [[John Cena]] and [[Randy Orton]] for the [[WWE Championship]]. Orton claimed that he never faced Cena in a one-on-one WWE Championship match.<ref name="Backlash - Cena vs Edge vs Orton vs Michaels">{{cite web|first= Louie|last=Dee|title=Survive and Conquer|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/matches/39606521/results|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-04-29]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref><ref name="Vengeance - Cena vs Foley vs Lashley vs Booker vs Orton">{{cite web| first=Louie|last=Dee|title=Five alive|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/vengeance/matches/4081164/results|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-06-24]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> On [[July 23]] edition of ''RAW'', Orton was finally granted his one-on-one WWE Championship match with Cena after he delivered an RKO to Cena.<ref name="RAW - Cena & Michelle vs Umaga, Cade & Murdoch">{{cite web|first=Corey|last=Clayton|title=One bad apple leads to Dominator destruction|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/07232007|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-23]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> Orton went on to attack Cena on an edition of ''[[WWE Saturday Night's Main Event|Saturday Night's Main Event]]''.<ref name="SNME - Cena vs Carlito">{{cite web|first=Corey|last=Clayton|title=Legend Killer Strikes On Saturday Night|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/snme/articles/ortoncena|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-08-18]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref>

The main feud on ''[[WWE Friday Night SmackDown!|SmackDown!]]'' was between [[The Great Khali]] and [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] for the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]]. The feud had started on [[July 6]] edition of ''SmackDown!'' when Khali put an open challenge for any WWE superstar to face him at [[The Great American Bash (2007)|The Great American Bash]].<ref name="SmackDown! - Khali challenge">{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Rote|title=A big surprise|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07062007|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-06]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> Batista accepted the challenge and on [[July 13]] edition of ''SmackDown!'', their match was final after a contract signing.<ref name="SmackDown! - Contract Signing">{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Rote|title=Officially on|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07132007|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-13]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> But, on [[July 20]], [[Adam Copeland|Edge]] was forced to vacate the World Heavyweight Championship due to an injury. That night, a 20-man battle royal for the World Heavyweight Championship occurred which Khali won<ref name="Khali World Champion">{{cite web| title=The Great Khali's first World Heavyweight Championship reign|url= http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/worldheavyweight/5079750|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> last eliminating Batista and [[Glen Jacobs|Kane]]. Batista and Kane were booked by [[Theodore Long]] in a [[List of professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|Triple Threat match]] against Khali for the title at The Great American Bash.<ref name="SmackDown! - World Title">{{cite web|first=Lennie|last=Difino|title=Giant change to Friday nights|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07202007|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-20]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> At the event, Khali retained his title.<ref name="The Great American Bash - Khali vs Kane vs Batista">{{cite web|first=Mike|last= McAvennie|title=The Great Khali wins the big one|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/matches/408116411/results| publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-22]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> On [[July 27]] edition of ''SmackDown!'', Khali celebrated his World Heavyweight Championship victory but the celebration was afterwards crashed by Batista who challenged Khali to a match for the title at SummerSlam.<ref name="SmackDown! - Khali Celebration">{{cite web|first=Alissa|last=Fuhrman|title=Who's ready to clash after The Bash?|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/07272007|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-27]]| accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref>

The main feud on the ''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling (WWE)|ECW]]'' brand was between [[John Hennigan|John Morrison]] and [[CM Punk]] for the [[ECW Championship]]. Morrison had retained the ECW title against Punk at The Great American Bash.<ref name="Great American Bash - Morrison vs Punk">{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Rote|title=Morrison enlightens the Straightedge Superstar|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/thegreatamericanbash/matches/42789821/results|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-22]]| accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> After defeating [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Elijah Burke]] in a triple threat match,<ref name="ECW - Punk vs Dreamer vs Burke">{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Rote|title=A chance for fame|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/07312007|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-07-31]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> Punk went on to defeat Morrison in a 15 Minutes of Fame match to earn himself a title match at SummerSlam.<ref name="ECW - Punk vs Morrison">{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Rote|title=CM Punk breaks on through|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/4791328|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-08-07]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref>

===Event===
Before the event went live on pay-per-view, [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[Lance Cade and Trevor Murdoch]] defeated [[Paul London and Brian Kendrick]] in a [[List of professional wrestling slang#D|dark match]].<ref name="match-dark">{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Martin|title=Result of Dark Match that took place before SummerSlam tonight in NJ |url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1188182303.shtml|publisher=WrestleView|date=[[2007-08-26]]|accessdate=2007-10-31}}</ref><ref name="SummerSlam - Dark match">{{cite web|url=http://www.hoffco-inc.com/wwe/ppv/ppv/sum07.html|title=SummerSlam 2007 review|publisher= hoffco-inc.com|accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref>

[[Image:Kane Entrance.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Glen Jacobs|Kane]] performing his signature entrance routine before his match against [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]].]]

The first match that aired was [[Glen Jacobs|Kane]] versus [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]]. Kane entered the match with a rib injury, after an [[Shillelagh (weapon)|Shillelagh]] attack by Finlay two weeks before the event. In the match, Kane quickly got the upper hand unloading his anger on Finlay. The momentum shifted, when Finlay managed to knock Kane of the top rope, causing his ribs to hit the top turnbuckle. Finlay continued attacking the injured ribs, applying several submission moves. Kane, however, managed to regain the momentum after hitting an Enzuigiri on Finlay. After that move, Finlay wasn't able to hit any major attacks on Kane, before he hit Kane with a Shillelagh, handed to him by [[Dylan Postl|Hornswoggle]]. However, Kane won the match after he sidestepped a shoulder block by Finlay and managed to perform a chokeslam on him.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Kane vs Finlay">{{cite web|first=Louie|last=Dee|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/390008831211/results/ |title=Let the Party begin|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SS WrestleView Report">{{cite web|first=Adam| last=Martin|title=SummerSlam PPV Results - 8/26 - East Rutherford, NJ (Cena/Orton)|url= http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1188182785.shtml|publisher= WrestleView|date=[[2007-08-26]]|accessdate=2007-11-16}}</ref>  

Next was a [[List of professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|Triple Threat match]] for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship]] involving [[Eddie Fatu|Umaga]], [[Carly Col<U+00F3>n|Carlito]], and [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Kennedy]]. In the match, Kennedy tried to get Umaga to help him eliminate Carlito, but Umaga instead started to fight both men, which he did successfully until Kennedy from outside the ring distracted Umaga in his attempt to hit a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Hip attack|Samoan Wrecking Ball]] on Carlito, allowing Carlito to dropkick Umaga out of the ring. Kennedy quickly attacked Umaga, finally kicking him into the ring steps, before getting himself back in the ring, where Carlito already awaited him. The match went back and forth between the two, with Umaga recovering on the outside. Umaga then managed to drag Kennedy to the outside and went on to assault Carlito with several high impact moves, before Kennedy hit him with a television monitor. Carlito and Kennedy then formed an alliance, but Umaga was able to keep the upper hand. In the end, Kennedy hit Carlito with a [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry slam|Green Bay Plunge]], but received a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Throat thrust|Samoan Spike]] himself, after which Umaga was able to win the match.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Triple Threat">{{cite web|first=Greg|last= Adkins|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/3900088312/results/|title=Double bulldozing... but barely|publisher=WWE| accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

[[Image:Rey3 WrestlemaniaRevenge.JPG|left|thumb|150px|[[Oscar Gutierrez|Rey Mysterio]], who faced off against [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]].]]

The third match was [[Oscar Gutierrez|Rey Mysterio]] versus [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]], which was Mysterios first match after his knee injury. At the beginning of the match, both men kept distance to each other, before performing several high-flying moves on each other. Guerrero then started to attack Mysterio's injured knee, but Mysterio was able to reverse the attempts. The match went back and forth, with both men attacking the others knees, mostly with submission moves. Guerrero managed to get the upper hand, but wasn't able to end the match at this point. The momentum shifted when Mysterio kicked Guerrero out of the ring and hit him with a senton. He went on with some of his signature aerial moves, winning the match after reversing a vertical suplex to a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Tiger Feint Kick|619]] and hitting him with a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Springboard splash|Springboard Splash]], which helped Mysterio win the match.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Mysterio vs Guerrero">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/390008832/results/|title=Mysterio soars in his return|publisher=WWE|accessdate= 2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

Next was an [[WWE Brand Extension|Interpromotional]] [[WWE Diva|Divas]] [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|Battle Royal]] involving [[Beth Phoenix]], [[Michelle McCool]], [[Torrie Wilson]], [[Melina Perez|Melina]], [[Mickie James]], [[Jillian Hall]], [[Barbie Blank|Kelly Kelly]], [[Kristal Marshall]], [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]], [[Layla El|Layla]], [[Maria Kanellis|Maria]], and [[Brooke Adams (model)|Brooke]]. After the bell rung, the women quickly formed formations fighting each other. Brooke was the first woman eliminated, after Beth Phoenix was able to slam her over the top rope. Shortly afterwards Jillian Hall performed a shoulder block on Maria, eliminating her. Layla was the third woman eliminated, being thrown out of the ring by Melina. Kristall was then able to eliminate Victoria, kicking her threw the ropes, but got eliminated herself, after Mickie James sidestepped Michelle McCool, causing her to hit Kristall instead. On the other side of the ring, Beth Phoenix easily eliminated Kelly Kelly with assistance of Jillian Hall. Jillian Hall then tried to throw Mickie James out of the ring, but while Mickie able to hang on to the ropes, Torrie Wilson helped her by throwing Jillian over the top rope top eliminate her. However, Mickie was eliminated shortly afterwards when Melina hit a shoulder block on her, when she climbed back in the ring. The two remaining Smackdown divas, Michelle McCool and Torrie Wilson, then worked together to eliminate Melina, leaving only Beth Phoenix in the ring with them. The two continued their alliance, but Beth Phoenix was able to get the upper hand, eliminating first Torrie Wilson and then Michelle McCool to win the match and a future title shot for the [[WWE Women's Championship]].<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Divas Battle Royal">{{cite web|first=Greg| last=Adkins|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/39000883122/results/|title=Phoenix rising|publisher=WWE| accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

Just when the match was over, [[Alvin Burke, Jr.|Montel Vontavious Porter]] came to the ring, challenging [[Matt Hardy]] to a beer drinking contest. Hardy declined, but named [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] his replacement. Austin came to the ring, drinking his first beer and started mocking MVP, doing several warm-up exercises, similar to those, MVP did before his previous challenges to Hardy. Just when they grabbed their first beer to start the contest, Austin delivered a [[Stunner (professional wrestling)|Stone Cold Stunner]] to MVP. He then celebrated with his signature beer bash, before leaving the ring.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="MVP vs Austin">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/39000883121/results/|title=Austin serves MVP the sting of beers|publisher=WWE| accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

[[John Hennigan|John Morrison]] versus [[CM Punk]] for the [[ECW Championship]] was next on the [[Undercard|card]]. Morrison quickly got the upper hand in this match, taking down Punk, but Punk quickly reversed with some kicks to the head of Morrison. The match went back and forth, with Morrison applying a choke hold on Punk, who was however able to get out of the hold and build some offense himself, scoring two near falls. Once with a rollup and then after reversing a catapult move by Morrison to a high cross body. Punk went on with a step up Enzuigiri and a cover, but Morrison managed to kick out again. Morrison then was able to build some offense himself with a neckbreaker on Punk, but wasn't able to win the match here. Punk then continued with a Moonsault from the top rope, but Morrison kicked out again. The momentum shifted when Morrison managed to reverse a [[Professional_wrestling_aerial_techniques#Frankensteiner|Poison Rana]] by Punk and won the match by rolling up Punk, using the ropes for leverage.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="SummerSlam - Morrison vs Punk"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

[[Image:Triple H Pointing Melbourne 10.11.2007.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Triple H]], who faced off against [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]].]]

The sixth match of the evening was a match between the returning [[Triple H]] and [[Booker Huffman|King Booker]], who claimed to be the only king in the WWE. Triple H started the match with some right hands and an irish whip into the corner, before taking Booker to the outside with a clothesline. He then continued his attacks on the outside with some hard punches, before getting him back into the ring. There, Booker managed to get some offense going with a few punches of his own, but Triple H quickly regained the upper hand with a facebuster, after an irish whip from Booker. However, he wasn't able to pin Booker yet. Instead, Booker gained the momentum, after Sharmell distracted Triple H, allowing Booker to assault his injured leg. Triple H then somehow managed to apply a figure four leg lock on Booker, but Sharmell interfered again with a thumb to his eye, allowing Booker to break the hold and score near fall. With the momentum on his side, Booker continued his offense on Triple H, taking him down several times. However, the momentum shifted again, after Triple H blocked Bookers punches and was able to whip him to the outside, where he drove Bookers head into the ring steps. Back in the ring, Triple H hit a Spinebuster and quickly went for his signature finisher move [[Facebuster#Double underhook facebuster|Pedigree]], which Booker managed to block. Booker then hit a [[Powerslam#Side slam|Book End]], but Triple H managed to kick out of the following cover. Booker then tried to hit a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Somersault legdrop|Top rope somersault legdrop]], Triple H however rolled out of the way and got the pinfall after hitting a [[Facebuster#Double underhook facebuster|Pedigree]], winning the match.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="HHH vs Booker">{{cite web|first=Corey|last=Clayton |url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam07/matches/390008831/results/|title=The proper pedigree: Triple H shows Booker who<U+2019>s king| publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

The Co-Mainevent was next, with [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Champion]] [[The Great Khali]] defending his title against [[Dave Bautista|Batista]]. The match started with Khali powering Batista into the corner, where he hit Batista with some punches. The referee separated the two, allowing Batista to get back on his feet. Batista then tried to get some offense going himself, but his punches showed no effect and when he performed a running shoulderblock, Khali got his foot up, knocking Batista down hard. He continued by kicking Batista out of the ring and as Batista tried to get back in the ring, Khali hit him with his signature [[Professional wrestling attacks#Overhead chop|Chop]]. Batista wasn't able to get any offense going at this point, taking a vicious beatdown by Khali. Khali then tried to apply his [[Professional wrestling holds#Clawhold|Vice Grip]] on Batista, who was able to overpower him, hitting a [[Professional wrestling throws#Spinebuster|Spinebuster]] on Khali. However, when he then went to the top rope, Kahli caught him, hitting a [[Chokeslam#Two handed chokeslam|Two Handed Chokeslam]], but Batista somehow managed to kick out of the cover. A frustrated Khali then took a chair and drove it in Batistas back, which left the referee no other choice than ending the match with Batista winning, but Khali retaining his title.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="SummerSlam - Khali vs Batista"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>

[[Image:Orton 05.jpg|left|thumb|150px|[[Randy Orton]], who challenged [[John Cena]] for the [[WWE Championship]].]]

Now it was time for the mainevent of the evening, with [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[John Cena]] defending his title against [[Randy Orton]]. After the referee checked both men, the two started a staredown, followed by a headlock by Cena. Orton managed to get to the ropes, forcing Cena to break the hold. He then applied a headlock himself on Cena, taking the Champion down, but Cena reversed, nearly locking in his signature [[Professional wrestling holds#STS|STFU]]. Orton quickly regained the upper hand, beating down Cena. He clearly dominated the match at this point, blocking every kind of attacks by Cena. Orton nearly won the match here, after he knocked Cena off the ring, with Cenas head bouncing of the announce table. He continued his beatdown with several punches and submission holds, but Cena refused to give up at this point. Although he also kicked out of several pinning maneuvers, he wasn't able to get any offense going. The momentum shifted when Cena powered out of another chokehold, slamming Orton into the corner and hitting his [[Professional wrestling attacks#Fist drop|Five Knuckle Shuffle]] on Orton. He then went for his [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]], but Orton countered into an inverted neckbreaker. Orton then was able to hit an [[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]] on Cena, but Cena kicked out of the cover. Orton then went for another [[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]] and although Cena was able to block it, he was knocked to the outside where Orton drove him into the ringsteps. Cena was again able to kick out of the cover and was even able to hit a [[Neckbreaker#Neck snap|running neck snap]] on Orton. When he then tried to climb the top rope, Orton quickly followed, hitting several punches. Orton then tried to hit Cena with a [[Professional wrestling aerial attacks#Super|Super]] [[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]], but Cena knocked him off the top rope and then to the ground with a legdrop. He tried to end the match with an [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]] then, but Orton blocked, knocking down Cena. With Cena in position, Orton went for a running punt then, but Cena reversed, locking Orton into his [[Professional wrestling holds#STS|STFU]]. Orton managed to get to the bottom rope, forcing a frustrated Cena to break the hold. In his frustration, Cena ran right into an [[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]], but was again able to kick out of the cover. He then managed to hit Orton with a vicious [[Professional wrestling throws#Fireman's carry takeover|FU]], finally winning the match.<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="SummerSlam - Orton vs Cena"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/> 	

===Aftermath===
MVP and Matt Hardy's rivalry was settled down after they won the [[WWE Tag Team Championship]] on [[August 31]], [[2007]] edition of ''SmackDown!'' by beating [[Deuce N' Domino]].<ref name="SmackDown! - MVP & Hardy vs Deuce N' Domino">{{cite web| first=Lennie|last=Difino|title=Tumultuous tag team|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08312007/articles/tumultuoustagteam|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-08-31]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref><ref name="MVPHardy1">{{cite web|title=MVP and Matt Hardy's first Tag Team Championship reign| url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/wwetag/18711854111|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> Umaga went on to lose the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship]] to [[Jeff Hardy]] on [[September 3]] [[2007]] edition of ''RAW''.<ref name="RAW - Hardy vs Umaga">{{cite web|title=Sweet redemption|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/09032007/articles/sweetredemptionforhardy|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-09-03]]|accessdate= 2007-11-21}}</ref><ref name="Hardy1">{{cite web|title=Jeff Hardy's first Intercontinental Championship reign|url= http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/36442661111|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-11-16}}</ref>

At [[WWE Unforgiven#2007|Unforgiven]], Beth Phoenix received her shot at the [[WWE Women's Championship]] against [[Candice Michelle]]. Michelle retained the title.<ref name="Unforgiven - Michelle vs Phoenix">{{cite web|first=Greg|last=Atkins|title= No glory for the Glamazon|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/unforgiven/matches/48366502/results|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-09-17]]| accessdate=2007-11-23}}</ref> On [[September 4]] edition of ''ECW'', CM Punk defeated John Morrison in a fourth and final match to win the ECW Championship.<ref name="ECW - Punk vs Morrison Title">{{cite web|first=Craig|last=Tello|title=Commencing a new era of Punk|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/09042007/articles/commencepunkera|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-09-04]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref><ref name="Punk1">{{cite web|title=CM Punk's first ECW Championship reign|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/history/ecwchampionship/20070901punk|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref>

On [[August 31]] edition of ''SmackDown!'' Rey Mysterio, Finlay, Kane and Batista participated in a 4-man Championship Competition tournament. Mysterio defeated Batista and Finlay in the tournament and thus became the #1 contender to the World Heavyweight Championship.<ref name="SmackDown! - Mysterio vs Finlay">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|title=Mysterio becomes top "David" against World Champion "Goliath"|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08312007/articles/reybecomesno1contender|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-08-31]]| accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> On [[September 7]] edition of ''SmackDown!'', Mysterio defeated Chavo Guerrero in an "I Quit match". After the match, he was brutally injured by The Great Khali until Batista made the save. Batista was then also included in Mysterio vs Khali match for the World Heavyweight Championship at Unforgiven.<ref name="SmackDown! - Mysterio vs Guerrero">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|title=And Batista makes three|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09072007/articles/andbatistamakesthree|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-09-07]]|accessdate =2007-11-21}}</ref> At the event, Batista won the championship for a third time.<ref name="Unforgiven - Batista vs Mysterio vs Khali">{{cite web|first=Lennie|last=Difino|title=Destined for gold|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/unforgiven/matches/48366501|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-09-17]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref><ref name="Batista3">{{cite web|title=Batista's first World Heavyweight Championship|url= http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/worldheavyweight/50797501|publisher=WWE|accessdate=2007-11-16}}</ref>

On [[August 27]] edition of ''RAW'', John Cena faced King Booker in a non-title match. Cena, who was close of winning; was eventually attacked by Randy Orton and as a result, the match was over. Orton attacked Cena's father and kicked him a boot in his head after running.<ref name="RAW - Cena vs Booker">{{cite web|title=Cena's father taken to medical facility for tests| first=Bryan|last=Robinson|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/08272007/articles/testsforcenasdad|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-08-27]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> The two faced each other in a rematch at ''Unforgiven'' for the WWE Championship. Cena was disqualified in the match for continuously punching Orton. Orton won the match but not the title because a title never changes hands by countout or disqualification. Afterwards, Cena's father kicked in Orton's head<ref name="Unforgiven - Orton vs Cena">{{cite web|title=Rage of two Cenas unforgiving to Orton|first=Bryan|last=Robinson|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/unforgiven/matches/4836650/results|publisher=WWE|date=[[2007-09-17]]|accessdate=2007-11-16}}</ref> in the same way as Orton had kicked in his head one month ago.<ref name="RAW - Cena vs Booker"/>

==Results==
*'''[[List of professional wrestling slang#D|Dark match]]: [[Lance Cade and Trevor Murdoch]] defeated [[Paul London and Brian Kendrick]]'''<ref name="match-dark"/><ref name="SummerSlam - Dark match"/>
*'''[[Glen Jacobs|Kane]] defeated [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]] (8:48)'''<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Kane vs Finlay"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>
**Kane pinned Finlay after a [[chokeslam]].
*'''[[Eddie Fatu|Umaga]] defeated [[Carly Col<U+00F3>n|Carlito]] and [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Kennedy]] in a [[List of professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|Triple Threat match]] to retain the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship]] (7:22)'''<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Triple Threat"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>
**Umaga pinned Kennedy after a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Throat thrust|Samoan Spike]].
*'''[[Oscar Gutierrez|Rey Mysterio]] defeated [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.|Chavo Guerrero]] (12:05)'''<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Mysterio vs Guerrero"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>
** Rey pinned Chavo after a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Tiger feint kick|619]] and a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Splash|Pickin' The Dime]].
* '''[[Beth Phoenix]] won an [[WWE Brand Extension|Interpromotional]] [[WWE Diva|Divas]] [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|Battle Royal]] also involving [[Michelle McCool]], [[Torrie Wilson]], [[Melina Perez|Melina]], [[Mickie James]], [[Jillian Hall]], [[Barbie Blank|Kelly Kelly]], [[Kristal Marshall]], [[Lisa Marie Varon|Victoria]], [[Layla El|Layla]], [[Maria Kanellis|Maria]], and [[Brooke Adams (model)|Brooke]] (7:06)'''<ref name="SLAM! Review"/><ref name="Divas Battle Royal"/><ref name="SS WrestleView Report"/>
**Phoenix last eliminated McCool to become the #1 contender to the [[WWE Women's Championship]].
